The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                 
	 Calcutta: Gundappa Viswanath will receive the CK Nayudu Lifetime Achievement Award for 2007-08, according to information forwarded by the Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) Saturday.    
	Viswanath will receive the honour at the BCCI Awards ceremony, to be held in Mumbai on February 18. The award comprises a trophy, citation, and a cheque of Rs 15 lakh.    
	Virender Sehwag is the favourite to get the Polly Umrigar Award.     
	Meanwhile, the BCCI has appointed former secretary Niranjan Shah as the manager of the Indian team for the New Zealand tour.        
	 Calcutta: Cuttack will host this years Deodhar Trophy cricket tournament to be held from March 13-18, the Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) said Saturday. This year, the Deodhar Trophy will feature five zonal sides and one team from Zimbabwe.    
	Schedule    
	March 13: Central Zone vs North Zone; West Zone vs South Zone.    
	March 14: North Zone vs East Zone; South Zone vs Zimbabwe XI.    
	March 16: Central Zone vs East Zone; West Zone vs Zimbabwe XI.    
	March 18: Final.        
	 Calcutta: The International Cricket Council (ICC) president David Morgan and chief executive Haroon Lorgat this week met Cricket Australia officials in what is planned as a series of meetings between the world governing body and its stakeholders in a bid to achieving a closer working relationship with its members.        
	 Colombo: Sri Lanka Cricket, on Saturday, played down the incident of the Indian team turning up at the Sri Lankan Presidents party in casuals, flouting the dress code. Dhoni and his men had worn jeans and T-shirts.        
	 Perth: India were on Saturday relegated to Group II of the Asia/Oceania zone after their humiliating 0-3 defeat against Chinese Taipei in the Fed Cup play-off tie here. The Indian team could not win even a single match in the whole tournament. Rushmi Chakravarthi lost the first match 2-6, 5-7 to Hwang I-Hsuan and then Ankita Bhambri surrendered 5-7, 1-6 to Chan Chin-Wei.        
	 New Delhi: The Indian Boxing Federation (IBF) suspended Commonwealth bronze medal winner Manjit Singh for two years for failing a dope test. According to IBF sources, Manjit had tested positive for a banned steroid at a national camp last year. He has also been stripped of the silver medal he won in the national championships.         
	 San Diego: A final hole birdie saved Arjun Atwal as he made the cut in the $5.3 million Buick Invitation golf tournament here. Overnight leader Camilo Villegas (133) carded 70 for a one-shot lead.    
